text: Wow, that looks terrible.  I'm honestly not sure they could have made that movie even further from the actual plot of the original comics, movies, and tv series'.  Kusanagi has always known her past.  Yes, she doubted it a little once, in one scene, in the first movie, but she still knew who she was, past or no past.  And her being the first?  That takes away from the entire plot point of her being generic and using a common body for her own.  It's her doubting her identity because so many others have the same external shells.  In the series this was updated to her having a specifically important watch because it was an external memory device; something she comments that many cyborgs rely on.  And the soundtrack is miserable.  Couldn't they get Kenji Kawai to work on it to make it as amazing as the original?  Talk about trying to make a pale image through a cloudy mirror and selling it to the blind.

text: To anyone& everyone complaining about whitewashing over ScarJo's casting as The Major. In the original manga upon which the movie and all other subsequent versions are based, Motoko/The Major is stated as preferring European (i.e. Caucasian) bodies. This is a fact backed up by Shirow Masamune, The Series Creator, in the appendices of said manga and multiple interviews. So this isn't just a case of her being drawn to look European due to some artistic stylization and giving her a mukokuseki (stateless) appearance that is popular in manga and anime. It's due to The Major herself being mukokuseki/stateless. This is coming from someone who has had Ming Na Wen cast as The Major since 1997 or 98. Scarlet isn't my first choice, but I think she's a good choice and will play her well.

text: You guys are gonna have to accept one thing. Adaptions are never going to be spot on, Hollywood will never adapt anything right. Whether it's a book, anime or comic. They will never give a shit about the lore, they will never give a shit about the fans. What they want, is the masses. The standard consumer. I already knew the day they announced they were gonna make a GiTS adaption, that it'd be shite. BUT I'm gonna watch it, I'm not gonna watch it as a GiTS movie. I'm gonna watch it as a cyberpunk movie that lends from the GiTS universe. If you want to enjoy this movie or any adaption that comes out of Hollywood, I'd suggest you'd do the same. Otherwise you're just setting yourself up for disappointment, because lets be real here, you shouldn't expect anything nowadays. Never forget though, we still have the real GiTS and it will never leave.

text: Still not sure what to think of this. Parts of it looks like an amazing shot for shot live-action remake of the original anime, but other parts look like they didn't really use the original story about the puppet master. And in my experience, when film-makers try to adapt a popular franchise but then don't use the original story because they are desperate to make it "their own", that backfires in 10 out of 10 cases. That's why most movies based on video games fail: they don't use the original story from the games and instead write a shitty new story, not realising that most of the fanbase of the source material are fans BECAUSE of the original story.

text: I am a huge Ghost in the Shell fan. I have read the manga, watched the films, watched Stand Alone Complex, watched ARISE, etc. I have seen and read pretty much every major media around the Ghost in the Shell franchise.   This movie, to me, looks fantastic. Not only is the tone down very well, but the main part of the GitS Franchise is the philosophies and themes of "Identity". Even if you don't notices it right away, every character, plotline, and story involved with the series is connected to Identity. Not just of the Major herself, but also of the people she comes across and knows. This movie looks to be following those themes very well, and I can't wait to see what's in store.

text: I'm disappointed, I thought they would make a live action version of the animated movie Ghost in the shell. While some scenes are taken from the animation such as the water scene it seems that they made up own stuff a bit too much. (be advised I have not yet seen the complete series) As I recall Major was nothing fancy as 'The first' that would indicate she is the chosen one but she was simply one of many who developed to become more of a philosopher.   The invisibility was nothing built in to her body which seems to be the case in this trailer but rather a technology using a specific type of cloth. The Major and Batou had a long relationship even at the start of the animation and that is why they has such trust in each other in the trailer it is indicated that Batou is newly created.   This movie would do good to copy as much as possible from the animation not go their own way with things. Well I do hope it will be good anyway but probably not as I had hoped.

text: I feel like I shouldn't like this, because "Hollywood only cares about the masses, they don't respect source material, etc." But, as a fan of the GiTS franchise, I'm liking this so far. The issue with live-action movies based on anime is that usually the japanese studios don't have a big budget, so the CGI ends up sloppy-looking, and not enough money and time goes into casting and writing as it should. So Hollywood, with a much bigger budget, can improve on some of these issues. For example, the CGI looks beautiful in this trailer, (which is important in a cyber-punk world like GiTS's) and I, personally, like Scarlett's performance until now (as a side note, it can't be considered white-washing if the character isn't even Japanese in the first place). Don't get me wrong though. These are all PERSONAL OPINIONS based on solely THE TRAILER. So, the movie can still be crap. But I won't call it shit just now. I'll wait and see. I'll actually watch the movie before judging it. (excuse my english, it's not my native language)

text: Regarding the whitewashing issue, I'd like to offer a different view. I think the choice of lead actress is not (just) a case of Hollywood whitewashing.    I think the issues present in the GitS franchise are becoming more and more relevant to the collective thought and conversation, now that technologies that were until now seen as "future technology", such as robotic limbs and more complex AI are being developed. I think that the choice of lead actress is just better fit for this purpose of injecting these ideas for rumination and conversation in the western world.   Still, I think it's a shame that this movie was not made with an Asian lead actress, keeping to the original story and setting. However, I think the creator of GitS was aware of this live action movie's purpose of injecting these ideas into the mainstream when he said that he does not care about the choice of Caucasian lead actress.

Also, while I don't know how this is going to turn out, I really wish Hollywood would at least try to keep the theme of the source material, even if they need to change some parts for multiple audiences. text: The original anime was all about the nature of existentialism, consciousness, and the id with extreme focus on setting and mood.  There are entire scenes which contain only soundtrack music and technopunk backdrops.  Think "Blade Runner" on sake bombers and absinthe. If the director is good (and he is), he'll attempt to match the draw with a formulaic storyline which doesn't attempt to appear too high-brow for the average viewer but also doesn't resort to juvenile action sequences which Michael Bay is so fond of.  It's about time we had a more intelligent sci fi movie that DOESN'T pander to toyish Hollywood fare.

But no seriously they might mess this RE-MOVIE up by making it a """soapy""" """oranges story""",  boring """CSI mystery story""" and have CG special effects that have no impact or emotion at all. So what i'm saying is this RE-MOVIE could be tone death and suck? ya really suck. The OG-MOVIE was not an oranges story, it was a window to the way the world was, it was not soapy it was raw and lived in, it did have a little boring side but it's OK for exposition to be a little boring, and the CG/cell animation was good because all of it was done by professionals that where directed and or by guy's that made this stuff all by hand back in the day. I hope i'm wrong in any case and this RE-MOVIE gives my goosebumps and inspires me in some way.

text: I know everyone is upset with the white-washing of roles, and of course it's terrible that it has to happen, but movies are a business and having an internationally famous face is the best way to guarantee an audience and a return on the investment. However, by only casting the lead in this way, film companies can create their larger audience while allowing the other actors get better known, upping their chances of being in more productions themselves and getting to that internationally famous status.  Effectively, by white washing roles now then can help generate more actors from foreign backgrounds in the future!

text: I think Scarlett Johansson is a good choice for being cast as the Major, and judging from the trailer I can't imagine who would do a better job or play the role better than her, and yes I have seen the Japanese animated film Ghost in the Shell, as well as the series Stand Alone Complex. Most of the main characters don't look Asian, mind you there are some that do in the original animated film but the Major and Bato are not them, the look very Caucasian. I really don't understand why people are accusing this film of "white washing" when it's not there. I really hope that this film is a success and that it introduces more people to the awesome and cool story that is "Ghost in the Shell".  I know fans such as myself want this film adaptation of Ghost in the Shell to have the same look and feel of the original animated film, judging from the trailer it does a very good job. I really don't want this movie to end up like Dragonball: Evolution, that movie was just a mess and was not a good experience, and I don't think this film will end up in such an abysmal failure like that movie did.

text: Ok, once again this makes me a little more confident in this movie: they capture the aesthetic of both the movies and the series well with some interesting additions as well as the use of practical effects. However I still get this weird vibe from Scarlett's acting. Not in a "OMG they should've cast an asian actor OMG" rage fit, I'm trying to move away from that so I can more fairly judge this movie. It feels a little awkward, like they could've placed slightly more humanity behind her words. I get it, she's a robot, but even in the manga and anime the Major had at least a little sense of humor despite the fact she never even blinked. However if they can pull of the "emotionless girl" trope with Scarlett like they've done in the past then all the more power to them.

text: Aesthetically this movie looks fantastic but it's a crying shame they didn't cast an Asian actress in the lead role. Scarlett Johansson isn't a talented actress. She plays the same character in all her action movies without even a slight nuance. So if anyone wants me to believe the producers were just prioritizing talent over race, all I can do is laugh. There are 7 billion people on this planet. It is a racist suggestion that there aren't incredibly talented actors and actresses of every race and it's insulting to my intelligence if you expect me to believe the only motivation here isn't money. They just want to trade in on Johansson's fame, despite the fact that numerous actors of color have demonstrated that they can play leads in films that go on to be wildly profitable.  And it just adds insult to injury that she's not even a good actress. Is there a single credible reason why someone like Rinko Kikuchi couldn't play Kusanagi?

text: I understand why many Americans (yes, Americans, not Japanese, not Europeans, not Koreans or anyone else, just Americans) still hate the idea of Scarlett playing a character previously portrayed as Asian. If this was instead a biography film starring real-life people and the main character was black but instead he was played by a white dude, you would be angry at Hollywood for whitewashing history. HOWEVER this is not a biography film, this is a fictional film and you people are angry not because of whitewashing but because Hollywood had the chance to create new fame and fortune for the latest Asian American movie star of what many of you feel is a highly underrepresented group in America but instead Hollywood played it too safe and wanted Scarlet, not because she was white but because she was famous and would guarantee the movie a lot of money. Many of you fellow Americans are not angry because of whitewashing, you guys are angry because you feel Asian Americans have been underrepresented more than any other "race" or group in American entertainment, specifically blockbuster movies.

text: Lots of people complain about Scarjo being a bad choice for Motoko, but rarely mention the other characters.WHO THOUGHT IT WAS A GOOD IDEA TO HAVE THAT GUY PLAY BATOU? HE LOOKS LIKE A BAD COSPLAY!But, yeah, Scarlet is a terrible choice for the character, for a variety of reasons besides just not being Asian.Her and the director of the film don't really seem to get the character, one of the other teasers showed her shaking in fear quite noticeably while aiming a pistol, which doesn't really fit the character's rather stoic reactions to dangerous situations, nor does she have the significant uncanny valley effect present in the oshii film this adaption seems to be mostly basing itself on, trading creepy, doll like eyes with a permanant thousand yard stare for that thing Scarlet frequently does where her eyes are looking slightly away from each other.She also has a completely different look from the character, major in the mango and anime had more of an 80's female bodybuilder physique, with the excessive tan being absent in the anime, Scarlet on the other hand is just built like a fairly average woman, which along with losing floofy hair for what looks like a bad wig cut up by a five year old, and the camo suit having a completely generic design which loses the skin tight, vacuum fitted latex look of the original to cater to the average American's irrational fear of nipples, makes the character design look far, far worse, it loses everything that made the original unique and memorable....and she's not Asian. Anyone who thinks Scarlet was a good choice for this role is absolutely delusional, having a bad imitation of a character's hairstyle =/= portraying them faithfully.

text: I watch this with a mixture of excitement and disgust.   Excitement because a few things here really look promising. But a lot of it may be just the GITS fanboy inside of me. And the producers should be very aware of the fact that, using so much original material (scenery/story) will inevitably make people compare. And if your movie looks worse than what was produced 1995, you know you're not doing it right, right? So I feel disgust because they handled a lot of the sourcematerial worse than the anime movies/series. And with the animes handrendering technics, especially of the first movie, they had it a lot harder to control the visuals then the CGI nowadays. Yet composition and detail looks partially worse than in 1995. And I am also worried. They seem to try to cramp far too much material into one story, which was used for many different storylines over years, instead of focusing more of their energy into less, to creat truly perfect scenery and story. I'd rather watch a shorter good movie than a longer worse one. Lets see how this all turns out. But I would keep my hopes low, to not suffer even more dissapointment.  Some feelings I felt while watching: 1. Major leaps from the tower (yes yes yes!!), breaks the window and jumps into the room (wait what?!). Really really hope these where footage from 2 different scenes.  2. CGI and movement of the major are lacking the grace, beauty and fluidity. This is an action SciFi, please use budget where it matters. 3. From a realistic perspective, Robo-Geishas should be stunningly beautiful, but they made them just look like cool robots, defeating the purpose of them being Gaishas in the first place. From an artistic standpoint, the contrast between the beauty of traditional Geishas and the technical, cold complexity of advanced machinery is what makes Robo-Geishas so great in my eyes. 4. The scenery of the normal streets lack the overcrowded details of the original, makes the scenery feel somewhat empty for me. 5. They tryed to use the color scemes in the originals as guides, but in the scenes they fail to replicate it, it really stands out.

text: scarlett johansson looks good for the role but I dont think the atmosphere really captures the original too well. It does not seem CYBERPUNK as much.. just kinda looks like a modern city with unnecessarily large holograms  with couple random avant garde fashion people in the streets or something. Seriously they just took a video of today's everyday streets and just threw in some floating koi fish and thats it. I expected more dystopian cyberpunk city in a night setting and more mechs with hundreds of different immaculately moving parts. And more WIRES, TONS and TONS of looping and spiraling wires connected to body parts which pretty much defines the gritty look of ghost in the shell. They did have little bit of that with the monks at the end but WTF? Just ONE wire for each person? There should be at least 10 wires or something. Man, that just looks shallow. It doesnt even have a spider tank probably because CG team could not dare to manage it. They really did not make this look good even with the original that had amazing visuals to use as reference.  I said scarlet johansson looked good for the Kusanagi role but when she said "maybe next time you can design me better", her delivery was very weak. Kusanagi Motoko is very strong character and stern soldier. I can think of several better way of her saying something like that. She is also capable of extremely sophisticated acrobatic moves(cyborg and all) but all you really get in this video is typical asf slow motion wall running.. She also looks like shes just wearing a nylon tights btw. Why remake a 3D movie out of it if 2D original looks so much better? All their selling point in this video is pretty much straight from the original anyway(geisha robots, building dive, invisible fist fight on a water) No I havent seen the movie yet but I dont think it will be good.

author: Soichiro Ogura

text: It's almost as if people complaining about the Major being white haven't even seen a single iteration of the GitS franchise, but saw the name "Mokoto Kusanagi" assigned to a white woman and went full autism.  The Major is completely cybernetic, meaning that she could have any race and any appearance that the writer chose.   Additionally, her appearance has basically been completely ethnically ambiguous/neutral throughout the franchise and each iteration. The writer could have omitted the name "Mokoto" and simply call her "the Major" as most people in the series already do.  And there is nothing inherently Japanese about the themes and the story except that it takes place in Japan, and that it has Japanese people. But the story could take place literally anywhere with a city setting and the story would remain practically the same.

text: whoa, alright. I can tell you that this movie, if the trailers show where the movie's direction is going, it completely wrong. They are emphasizing the android bodies, which is in original film is not even an important part of the film. body enhancements are the normal. In fact, Togusa only has a memory upgrade and the rest of him is mostly human which leaves the rest of the team impressed and slightly bitter that he is able to keep up with the team without enhancements.  The main focus of the movie is when the a human not longer a human but something else. that is the real heart of the original film. in addition, it looks like this film is combining both Ghost in the Shell and Innocence and both of those movies have different topics.   my advice to anyone interested in this film, go watch the original animated films ghost in the shell and Innocence and just skip this.

text: I‚Äôm a huge anime fan, and I absolutely love seeing big budget adaptations of my favorite anime. Listen, I acknowledge that there‚Äôs a huge lack of Asian representation in Hollywood but this isn‚Äôt the movie to scream ‚Äúwhitewashing‚Äù about. Hollywood is a business, and they need to make a profit. Ghost In the Shell is a FRINGE anime whose core fanbase is not big enough to justify the multi-million dollar budget this film has. The studio had to hire an A-List star to draw in the general public, people who never heard of anime in their entire life.   We can‚Äôt have it both ways. Either they cast an unknown Asian actor and create a low budget indie movie (which would be horrible for this particular franchise) or cast a movie star and give this adaptation the budget it deserves. The latter option is a win/win for fans and the movie studio, who need a return on their investment.   We need to hold Hollywood accountable for not casting Asian actors in everyday tv shows and movies. Raise your voice and speak up for Asians not being in sitcoms and primetime dramas or movies without anything to do with sci-fi or fantasy. That‚Äôs when true change will happen.

text: Um... where is Section 9?  I did not see Togusa, Ishikawa, Saito, Paz, Borma, Azuma, Yano or Proto....And another thing, this origin story they are alluding to is way off canon. She was not maimed or mutilated and rebuilt by corporate assholes trying to turn her into a super weapon. (Way over used in movies already btw). Her plight is in finding her identity but because she never had a body to begin with, she has always been a consciousness inside of a machine. That is where the name "Ghost In The Shell" comes from. I will still see it and probably love it, but I think they could have stayed truer to the origin in the movies.

text: This is weirdly self-conflicting. There's a lot of scenes there that pull directly from the '95 movie, but also from the TV show, SAC, and yet more that are totally unrelated to anything presented in the franchise thus far. Also, the story premise they're presenting here is wildly different than that original movie or the TV shows. Although Kusanagi was always aware of her lack of a past, that was never a focus for her character or the story. Her past is only explicitly discussed in one episode of of SAC: 2nd Gig and only hinted at occasionally outside of that, but only as a way of commenting on certain events.  But all that said, Oshii seems to like it, so maybe there's enough here to make it work.

text: For the record, the 1995 Ghost in the Shell movie opens with this statement: "In the not so distant future, when the corporate networks fill the Earth with electronic and optical communication lines, but society has not yet been too computerized to erase nations and races..."  Anyone who says the characters' races don't matter cause their cyborgs wasn't paying attention to all the political subtext and commentary in SAC series.   Finally they are episodes in ghost in the shell where they meet  Caucasian  Americans and they look different from Motoko.  This proves at the VERY LEAST she isn't Caucasian.  "But but, scarlett johansson is a box office success thats why she was casted"  WRONG, the producers wanted Margot Robbie but she was filming tarzan and was booked with suicide squad.   "She wasn't white in the anime"  Actually she was, and in Arise you can very briefly see her parents.   "WHAT difference does it make"  well she works for a Top Secret Japanese Government agency,  Walking around looking like a Caucasian american women isn't the best disguise.     "But Japan makes our movies with ALL JAPANESE CAST, Are they racist!"  Well I can't speak for japan, but in here in the U.S. we are a melting pot. We have the most diverse country on earth and movies sometimes and SHOULD show that.  EDIT: IF you want to know why anime looks white, read this.  https://thesocietypages.org/socimages/2010/08/30/guest-post-why-do-the-japanese-draw-themselves-as-white/

text: I like how all of these people criticizing Scarlett Johansson as The Major simply don't understand how movies work.   Hollywood movies are all about making money. It's a business. If you make a movie based off of an anime film which isn't very well known in the U.S., use Japanese actors and actresses who aren't very well known, and expect the movie to make money, you're going to have a bad time.  Ghost in the Shell isn't Star Wars. You can't throw in actors that no one knows and get people to see it based off of the name alone. So, the only other thing you can do to get people to take notice of the film is to hire an A-list actress to take on the main role. Scarlett Johansson is the reason people who don't know what Ghost in the Shell is will see this movie. She's proven she can take on badass female leads, which The Major definitely is.   Besides, what makes The Major Japanese, aside from her name (Motoko Kusanagi)? She's a cyborg. She could have looked like anyone, of any ethnicity. In the original movie, she doesn't even look particularly Japanese. And her ethnicity, realistically, is irrelevant to the plot of the original movie. The movie could have taken place in any major city of the world, as long as the themes of identity and human interaction with technology were still present.  So, to everyone claiming whitewashing and all that bullshit, do some research into how Hollywood operates and stop spouting your idiocy. If there was an A-list Japanese actress who was ignored for Johansson, then you would have a point, but that's simply not the case.
author: Toaster Child

text: this plot looks... sort of not so much like a ghost in the shell story. The major was never hyper concerned with the cliche things like 'Where did I come from?' or 'People are apart from me, because I'm synthetic' nor did she ever say dumb things like "Maybe next time you can design me better". She has a real sense of humor about herself and the rest of her team,  she was NOT a broody Mary Sue. GitS isn't about Major Kusanagi it's about the society of future japan, and where things go from black and white to grey, and making her the entire focus of the movie doesn't make any sense. Even the title of the show, Ghost in the Shell, is a commentary on humanity and synthetics.

text: I honestly can't tell if this will be bad or not, which I guess is a good thing.  These western adaptations of eastern anime never work out, but you gotta at least appreciate the effort on display here.  I think this movie has a little too much of that "summer blockbuster" feel to it when Ghost in the Shell is supposed to be a deliberate and intelligent story peppered with the occasional grand action scene.  Anyway, it remains to be seen, but I hope this is good.  It looks like it could be.  P.S. I'm not sure if Scarlett Johansson was right for this role.  The Major is supposed to be a very confident and strong person, but Scarlett gives off a stoic and soft demeanor.  Watching the anime, The Major is like the most capable and intelligent operator in Section 9, and instantly gives off a lasting impression being such a well-rounded female lead character.  I fear that aspect of her character is lost in this casting, which is a shame, because Motoko (The Major) is one of the most endearing female characters in anime.

text: I'm alright with Scarlett being cast as Mak-, I mean, The Major. She has the character's looks and the sex appeal to sell the movie in the US. Batou's ethnicity has always been somewhat ambiguous, yet they lazily cast a white guy who doesn't really look the part. He has Batou's physique while shirtless, but just looks overweight with a coat on. Aramaki is supposed to be short, skinny, and non-combative, yet he waves a revolver around like Togusa, who's nowhere to be seen.  It's unsurprising that they took liberties with the fact that people in this world can switch into whatever bodies they want. But when you meld characters with distinctively different personalities like Aramaki and Togusa into something unrecognizable, this movie seems more like a money-grabber than a love letter to fans.

text: I consider myself a huge fan of Shirow's GITS, read the manga, watched both seasons of the TV series and of course the 1995 Movie as well as a sequel called Innosence. And being that guy who has all of that behind his shoulders is like being the worst critic for this upcoming adaptation, especially considering the fact that the story needed no adaptatio sincen the 1995 movie in itself is a fricking masterpiece that'll blow you away. I've said to myself that I should try to put off the scepticism till I see it of course because I still kind of had hopes for the adaptation...Buuut that was back when we only had those small teasers, when I saw this trailer I kind of figured out what this actually will be  - a Hollywood action flick with a bland plot that just took some cool concepts from the original story. So this is about some type of conspiracy behind Motoko's past? "They stole it" Really? Yet another "i-don't-know-my-past-those -bastards-took-it-from-me-for-whatever-evil-reason-jason-bourne" type thing just with Geishas and Lesbians and an occasional Takeshi instead of CIA guys? Come on!!!! Who plays Bato? The guy from Need For Speed, the guy who played a King in a WarCraft Movie? Couldn't they've tried harder to find someone who is at least as big as he should've been? Not to mention the totally different face. I mean COME THE F ON!!! Who is the guy at the end of the trailer? The Puppet Master?????? NOOO!!! Not like this please. I'm sure this will be a spit in the face of those who loves GITS like I do and for those unfamiliar with the franchise it will establish a wrongful opinion that GITS is some cyborg action flick with a generic plot. Don't get me wrong I want this to be good with all my heart, but something tells me it's just isn't going to be...

text: Let's ignore the SJW tantrum and get to the point.  From what can be seen here, Hollywood is going to screw up a great franchise.    Instead of a smart bad-ass battle hardened soldier and god level hacker who knows who she is, where she came from, where she's going, and who's ass she'll kick when she gets there, this film features a glum amnesiac.    Instead of a nebulous mystery like the puppet master, swarming threat like the stand alone complex, a calculating opponent like Goda, or an untouchable menace like the Laughing Man, this film has a bot which lost its old data files.    Instead of a subtext discoursing on the ontology and epistemology in a context where real and virtual merge to become inseparable, this film has angst.    This trailer has the films best parts, and there aren't any.

text: Idris Alba was cast as Heimdall in Thor. Michael B. Jordan was cast as Johnny Storm. Samuel Jackson was cast as Nick Fury. Lucy Liu was cast as Alex Munday in Charlies Angel's. Shawn and Marlon Wayans played white women in White Chicks.  These are all instances of actors being cast in roles of white characters, or in the case of the last example, portraying the reversal of the controversial "black face". There are many more examples to draw from. If you look at any of the other film industries around the world, they mostly cast actors of their respective nationalities. There are more examples of "white roles" being portrayed by other nationalities than any others. Trying to create a race based narrative for casting decisions is actually perpetuating the divide, so I say, stop being racist, and encouraging the exclusion of an entire race from a role. Perhaps they simply cast the best person for the role.

text: One thing I really liked about the original was that it dealt with very philosophical issues. For example, there was a part where the villain (a very advanced AI) demanded asylum because it was a sentient entity. Somebody barked "You're not! You're just a self preserving program!". To which it replied "By that rationale, I submit that your DNA is nothing more than a self-preserving program". That made me go "Oh wow, it has a point!". It actually made me think whether we are, in essence, just a very advanced computer program, which is a disturbing thought because I've always thought of computer programs as being very "limited", whereas I envision us humans as being superior because we have choice and free will to do what we want. But what if that's not the case, and what if the AI is right? That we're just like a computer program, and we don't really have choice or free will, that we're limited by our DNA just like the AI is limited by its programming? And if the AI is right, then how long before we create an AI that's so advanced that it would become morally unacceptable to simply shut it off because it's just too aware of itself? I think that was the unique thing about the movie, that it actually made me think. Whereas I can just turn my brain off and enjoy most movies, this one actually made me stop and ponder about, you know, life in general. I'm not getting that vibe from this movie as of yet. It just feels like a movie where the character has a personal quest, which has been done over and over again in one way or the other.

text: Okay, setting aside the divisive issue of the casting for a moment, and just focusing on the content...  ...What the hell is this? This plays like somebody watched the Mamoru Oshii film once, remembered all the cool action scenes, and completely ignored the strong characterization and intricate storytelling that makes the franchise as a whole so popular.  I don't know why they would give such a boring and generic character arc to a character as potentially interesting as the Major. I don't know what the hell Aramaki is doing standing over somebody with a revolver like some Yakuza hitman. I don't know where the Fuchikoma (or Tachikoma) are. I don't know how Michael Pitt's dialogue at the end is supposed to resemble anything the Laughing Man would ever say. And the actor delivering Batou's lines just sounds bored.  Artistic license is important, and telling new stories is important. But when you can replace the _Ghost in the Shell_ logo with an original title and just market this as an original film, that's a sign that you fucked up. Taking all of the recognizable names and a couple of set-pieces from an existing property and throwing everything else away is not the way to make a good adaptation.

text: To answer the two most common question people ask: 1.) Yes, this is an adaption from an anime. 2.) Don't worry on weather or not you saw the original, movie adaptions explain the story from beginning to end. For example, "The Shining" is a movie adaptation from author Steven King, but we all still understand the plot when we watch it even if we didn't read the book. Other classic examples include Fight Club, American Psycho, Silence of the Lambs, Trainspotting,  Apocalypse Now, and The Godfather.

text: The focus seems more on the "intrigue"' where Major come from, what the bad guys know she doesnt about the corporation that made her, etc. The original was more about the soul in a world of machine, the connexion between being, than about the "intrigue" itself. It was more a japanese theme, now we are more into typical Hollywood intrigue. Plus, Major was had a ambiguous ethnic look somewhere between Asian and Occidental, but Scarlett is 100% American looking. And Major was androgynous (except for the big boobs), she had strong muscular features in the anime (androgyneity is another strong theme in japanese animations along with occidental/oriental ambiguity), here she is the embodiement of american white feminity (i love Scarlett, but not the right casting)  Honestly, i am afraid Hollywood will lost the "Ghost" of this story, it soul, in favor to something more watchable for American public. But its hard to say for sure with a 2 minutes trailer. It could be that they focused on these aspects in the trailer to attract peoples and the film itself will have less white washing and will stay closer to the original spirit than this preview seem to let us know.    In short, the preview show a superficial recreation of the "shell" of the original with cute looking exotic imagery, but not of the "ghost"

author: Julio Munoz

text: This anime movie is so much deeper then this. These films will always look visually stunning but these "adaptations" constantly ruin the originals. The main source of these films/graphic novels, are filled with rich context and themes that make you wonder. What made Ghost in the shell so powerful along with other animes/graphic novels is the existential questions that are placed throughout the story. There are strong themes of identity in the original ghost in the shell, questions like  "what is consciousness?" This theme centers around the character and her not feeling that she needs to find out "who or what she is" but rather "what is"   This film feels like a dumbed down version of reinterpreted version of the original.

text: PLEASE enough about the Asian actress thing. üòë If you know the original movie, you know Major Kusanagi is drawn with a caucasian appearance, as are MANY main anime characters.  So much anime that is worth remembering has main characters drawn as 'white'.  The artists were Asian and that was their decision with their art.  Please, if you don't know classic Anime then you really shouldn't complain.  Go watch the original 1995 Ghost in the Shell PLEASE.. also Akira, Ninja Scroll, Patlabor, Vampire Hunter D, etc... get educated. ‚úì My biggest problem with this movie is the casting.  Scarlett is amazing in her own way but she's no Major.......  This movie doesn't need Scarlett.  It needs a physically perfect, somewhat absent faced SOLDIER.  The reason I watch the original again and again is because the Major kicks so much ass.  It's not her words that make me a fan.  It's her physicality.  Her strength.  Her top of the line BANGIN' Cyborg Body.  How Naive she is...  Scarlett is sultry.  We need a new face with the physicality of Adriana Lima combined with a top olympic athlete.  Such a huge disappointment from a huge fan like me.  üòîüòîüòî The other thing that scares me is the fact that some scenes in this trailer look almost IDENTICAL to scenes from the original Anime.  If you've seen the real life adaptation of "Blood, The Last Vampire" then you'll share with me in my fear of this being a let down...  Trying to replicate the exact Anime in a real life setting is kinda like eating reheated nachos.  It sucks.  Make new story lines and other kick ass settings.  That way we'll have nothing to compare it to.  I hope it's good.  I really do....  But if it sucks, as a huge fan of GITS....  I'll be pissed.  üçÄ

text: JohanssonOk, one minute was enough for me. Sorry, but I'm not buying any of this one the same level as I did the anime (Which I enjoy BTW) something about it comes off feeling strange in a "Fakey Movie effects" sort of way. It's missing something, and I don't quite know what that is. But you can feel the difference right away, and not in a good way. I'll get things thrown at me, but I don't like Scarlett Johansson in this role, or situation either. Overall, I think it's a fine application of the rule everyone seems to have forgotten: Never do in Live-Action what you can do in Animation, and never do in Animation what you can do in Live-Action. Sorry, but I think this one has "Turkey" written all over it, and not just because  it's mid-November.

text: I don't give a crap about "whitewashing", the character specifically states in SAC that she uses off the shelf bodies to make her less conspicuous, plus she keeps smashing them up so it makes sense for her to use a relatively cheap model.  What I do care about is the dumbing down of the philosophical aspect of the movie, which looks as though they've taken all the high concept thought provoking exploration of the nature of the self and what it means to be a human and reduced it down to "One woman's struggle to rediscover her past".  Dull american psycho-babble, self-help, Opera Winffrey, teen-angst melodrama.  Nice work people.  Still if it can do anything to introduce new audiances to the original Movie, the SAC and the Manga then it's not a bad thing, but for me this will never be "Ghost in The Shell"

text: The problem with this movie, or the casting is, that the source material is not really mainstream to begin with. I'm well aware, that the 1995 movie was successful and popular in it's own demographic area, but not outside of it. Now even if the manga/anime was popular outside it's mainstream genre, it still would need a marketable star to be bring in the profits that it is aiming for. And can someone name one Asian actress, or in particular a Japanese actress, that is popular and and fit enough to make this movie a blockbuster hit? In my honest opinion, it the character is portrayed in a dignified and tasteful manner, I don't care what ethnic background he or she has.

text: This is a show that had an episode where AI tanks were discussing and exploring their own consciousness, even mentioning Richard Dawkins; no reductionism necessary. There were enough elements in GITS to "cool-ify" for the commercial audiences and they could have layered it to maintain some sort of lifeline with the people who liked the philosophical exploration. No, it's not cool to change the story like this. The point of GITS is to explore what it means to be human in an increasingly fuzzy AI world, terrorism, war etc, from a multitude of perspectives. It never needed cheap cliches and there was intellectual respect for the audiences. Motoko Kusanagi is supposed be La  Femme Nikita's Madeleine level of greatness. Her exact LACK of identity crisis, capacity for emotional adjustment, strategic prowess, leadership and political skills ,used to be the most lovable things about her. Major is not reactionary and needy. I'm hoping it's just a bad trailer.

Yeah, the female lead was asian and the movie was very much inspired by mecha animes, and most people though the movie sucked for those sole reasons. Imagine if Ghost in the Shell had an asian lead, *so many people* wouldn't watch just because of that. So my hope is that by having a white lead, although it is sad, at least it makes people watch and enjoy, and then maybe watch the anime and realize it's still a good story even without a white protagonist. It's my hope that we can make people watch movies with asian characters and not assume it is bad.

text: It's a sad attempt by the so called "fans" who are not familiar with the Major's background to always bring up race when in the manga and anime her ethnicity was never disclosed. She can manifest herself into anything since she is an artificial intelligence with an artificial body but implanted with a human brain. "Artificial body" should give you a hint that she can look European, Japanese, African, or whatever ethnicity she chooses since she is now an artificial intelligence. In the anime she experiences plenty of near death scenarios to a point where her body is almost completely destroyed. She is brought back to life by her organization by fixing her all over again therefore, she can look different if her organization wishes by giving her another artificial body.   Masamune Shirow, the original author of the manga, indicated that the concept of GitS is global, meaning it is a story blended with Western and Japanese themes. The story was based on humanity's increasing reliance on the internet and technology, which is prevalent today. The advent of the internet in America, specifically Google, influenced the story and Masamune also researched studies from Japanese universities about technology's impact throughout the world therefore, the story is about humanity losing a sense of identity due to our reliance and obsession with technology.  Plus, I find it ironic when people say race when we are all human. What they mean is ethnicity. Either way, the Major has a dilemma about her identity, whether she is purely ai or human. In the anime she said she does not know if her memories are hers or from someone else since her brain was implanted.   However, she has grown so accustomed to her life as a cyborg agent owned by the Japanese government. Her body was manufactured by her organization so she is an important asset to them therefore, she lost her identity as a human when she had to undergo critical cybernetic enhancement as a very young child around the age of six.  Before anyone brings up her name being Motoko Kusanagi, well that does not automatically qualify her as being Japanese. My name is Christian Gonzales. People automatically assume that I am Hispanic when I am actually Filipino. I may be Filipino but I identify myself as American because I have never been nor grew up in the Philippines, so I don't know anything about their culture but America's. I have plenty of Korean friends who have names that don't sound like the culture of their ethnicity like Daniel Johnson or Michael Trenton. People come from all over the world so I would not be surprised to see an African or a European  with a Japanese name in Japan if they have breathe and lived the culture ever since they were born there.  Point is, the Major's ethnicity was never disclosed in the anime or manga but her race certainly was and that is maybe human (her human implanted brain) or maybe artificial intelligence. Also, there was the fact that as a child she had to undergo major cybernetic enhancement in order to live due to a life threatening accident.   The story is about her trying to find out her identity ever since she changed into an advanced cyborg.  Before you call me a bigot for supporting the whitewashing in the Hollywood film industry, of which there is, I don't see that applying in this setting. It is appropriate for someone like ScarJo to be casted in this story because she really pulls off the character of Major well. I am impressed by her performance so far, but I will reserve judgement about the film until it releases.   To reiterate, the Major is a character with a lost identity with a past of a human as a child but a current life of an artificial intelligence. She has a dual race as a  human and ai but an unknown ethnicity, and the story is not exclusively a Japanese concept but blended with Western and global influence.Ôªø

text: As someone who has never seen the anime, read the manga, and has only seen one of the anime movies, this looks pretty good. However... this IS a live action anime adaptation we're talking about here. They have so many opportunities to disappoint the fans and I'm sure they're going to find a way to do them all. Hopefully I'm wrong and we'll finally get the first GOOD live action anime adaptation... at least when it comes to an American film crew since there have been good anime live action films... just... all of them have been made in Japan. Maybe other film makers will be able to take notes and figure out how to make a good film. Maybe we'll be able to get a good Dragon Ball film instead of the train wreck that came out years ago. Maybe there'd be a possibility for the Death Note film to be decent.

text: I wonder how similar this will be to the previous GitS canon. In the manga/anime, Kusanagi was more or less pulverised in an accident as a child, and she became a full body cyborg afterwards. She learned to control her cybernetics while her brain was still young and flexible, and the reason she is badass was not because "[she] is the first of [her] kind!", but more that she is a prodigious mind naturally at home in a military grade full body prosthesis. In the first episode of Stand Alone Complex, the plot revolved around someone masquerading as a Geisha-sexbot, putting their own brain inside the full body prosthesis of a prominent Japanese politician. When she herself was "cyberized", a fellow survivor of the plain crash agreed to the same a couple of days after she visited him in her new body. I hope they don't butcher Kusanagi's character by making her awesome because she is some "chosen one", instead of a driven and intelligent woman pursuing a career in law enforcement.

text: I'm willing to give the movie a try. Honestly though, I'll be more surprised if it's actually good. Live action movies usually suck, so I'm hoping that they've at least done a decent job with this one. I'm always willing to give movies a chance--especially considering how much I love all the GitS anime, manga and guides. As far as saying most Japanese people don't care about the casting, that may or may not be true. I don't think that the opinions of few represent the opinions of many. So unless someone polls most or every single Japanese Ghost in the Shell fan in Japan, that statement is a bit hard to accept. Not saying it's right or wrong, but it really doesn't prove anything except for there are 'some' Japanese people who don't mind. Some might actually hate it, but they're less likely to complain about it since it's not anything pressing. It's just a movie. Also, Sam Yoshiba, a publisher at Kodansha, said he was fine with the Scarlett Johansson. As far as I know, the author/creator never stated that him self.  While I understand both sides of the argument, I also understand that this is an adaptation. Even the people over at Kondansha realized (and said) that since this was a Hollywood movie, they never even expected Motoko's actress to be Japanese. They never said she was or wasn't Japanese. Just that considering who was spearheading the movie, they didn't expect her to be. Take that statement as you'd like. Not saying anybody is wrong; to each their own. I'm willing to give it a try.

text: Reposting from a Facebook post I made, so the formatting is kinda weird, but  Since this is apparently a lose adaptation of SAC:2nd GIG, I have no idea why they're recreating iconic scenes from the 1995 movie. Not to mention, there isn't nearly enough screen time to fully dedicate to the Individual Eleven, so it's strange that they're even featuring Kuze. The decision to give focus to the Major's backstory is also an odd one, considering that a broader understanding of the setting and the way that it relates to the sense of self is needed to appreciate her background as a whole. Not to mention, the notion that the Major could be the only one of anything is incredibly strange, considering that the usual GiTS overarching theme of questioning the self only holds up when ones body is no longer a subject of individuality.     It's also concerning that we don't see the rest of Section 9. While I can understand the exclusion of Pazu, Bouma, and Seito, I'm concerned that we don't see any of Togusa, considering how essential of a supporting character he is for most of SAC.     The action shots look incredibly un-GiTS like. Most of what made the Major a strong character was her ability to lead and command others, both during combat and out. She rarely fought alone (only twice in the 97 movie, and only around three times, give or take, in SAC), and she was never did crazy acrobatics. While this change is understandable in the context of Hollywood movie, more considerations should have been taken to accommodate for the tone of GiTS.

text: Edit2**Hodoss expertly counters my ramblings here, so make sure to read his response and my response to him further down if you actually give two flips about these comments. It's interesting to see the diversity of opinion on something like this!  Call me a "SJW" if you want, but I have a huge issue with whitewashing.  I'm a pretty race neutral kinda guy, I'm cool with anyone doing whatever and think racial "roles" are bullshit (ie music genres unbound by race, using whatever language you wish, adopting cultural customs from anywhere, etc.).  But why take an East Asian character and cast a white woman for it (who I will mention costs a pretty penny, Johannson isn't a C-Lister) when Hollywood and other film centers are filled to the brim with young Asian actors willing to do a role for cheaper to get their foot in the door in a massive way?   Why is everyone except Takeshi Kotano also whitewashed?  There's a case to be made for Bollywood adaptations not featuring actors of other races, because while India is ethnically diverse it is not so racially diverse.  Hollywood however is not Bollywood, it's a district of one of the most ethnically and racially diverse cities in one of the most diverse states in all of America.  I don't think there's malicious intent, like some cuckoos, but I think Hollywood and producers need to dig their heads out of their ass and realize there's more to film than just their usual recruiting pool.  People have argued that since the story of the Major and the film overall is a very universal one, that race does not factor into it.  That is also a perfectly reasonable argument, so don't take me as someone who's choosing a "side".  Besides that, this trailer bugs me on another level.  It's taking scenes from the 1995 film, so I assume it is a remake of the original film and maybe parts of GitS 2.0: Innocence and not Standalone Complex or Arise.  If that's the case, then why is it focusing so much on the Major's background?  1995 never really focused on where Kusanagi came from, it instead grappled with where she was going, what the new world and relationships between beings was like, even just the question of the nature of consciousness to begin with.  It was action-heavy, but it took time to focus on the internal narratives of each character or conflict in stride rather than just as a background to throw action scenes over.  The boat scene between Batou, the discovery of the Ghost,  the showdown, the epilogue conversation;  these were all narrative-crucial parts of 1995, and from this trailer I get none of that.  If the producers wanted to stay faithful to the original, why not take a more daring approach and leave us with questions?  Or hell, just pull a Full Metal Jacket trailer and distill your entire movie into a few frames and quotes?  As it stands, I know what this looks like: Robocop.  It looks like anime Robocop, and not the good one, the remake that was just meh.*  Whatever, I've spent way too much time thinking about a dumb adaptation I probably won't see unless it gets good reviews or an anime-fan friend of mine recommends.  Just my two cents.  *Looking at it closer, I think it's more likely an adaptation of the original manga, so there's more material there to be adapted.  The general point remains, however.

text: I believe this will be a good film though it's clear the director and crew are going for a different storyline. In the anime, the major and the rest of section 9 aren't worried about their past or trying to find out who they are or were, but rather stoping political and criminal corruption in their city. Major accepts who and what she is because she has no choice and cannot change it. It's a very nihilistic and tragic order of events that show the risks of transhumanism and turning away from our humanity to seek a high level of existence. Still, I hope this movie can set a new standard for live action anime adaptations, and that it does well. I feel more people should give it a chance.

text: 1st, saying anime looks white is a bs reason to justify her being white. They don't look like any race. No one in real life has a triangle for a nose, eyes that huge, or natural purple/blue/green etc hair. The medium values simplicity for faces. Simply that.  I'm Asian and I think ScarJo is a great choice. Besides her being white being totally plausible within GITS' plot, here's another good reason. This movie cost a fortune to make. You need an A list actor that can make up the money used to make this movie just by her name and there are NO A-list Asian actresses. You think Hollywood is like "lets hire a white person cuz we hate minority?" NO. They arn't stupid. They know there will be backlash. Hollywood is a business. They respond to profit. If this movie succeeds =>  more anime films => more Asian themed films => more opportunity for Asian actors. You can't go from 0 to 100 just like that. I believe this is the first step in the right direction. They can't risk leaving this to any actor simply because she's Asian.   And here's another potential and unfortunate problem if she's asian. There are tentions between Japan, and China and Korea's government and a certain degree of racism between them (This is generalizing. Not saying all everyone hates each other) .  If she's not Japanese, (especially if the actor is Chinese) that's a huge major spit in the face to Japan, the origin of Gits. It will alienate Gits "original" audiences, limiting the search pool even further. I feel like ScarJo is a pretty good buffer for now.

text: Judging from this trailer, it looks faithful to the anime and is visually interesting. I just can't picture S.J. as the major, though. No, not because she's white, but for two reasons: One, Scarlett, in my opinion, is too famous. I think it would play better to bring in a relatively 'unknown' actress. All I see is Black Widow parading around as Motoko. I get it that production wants to draw in new viewers to the GIS franchise with a popular name, and I hope it works that way for them. Second, Scarlett, as fine an actress as she is, seems to me to have a perpetual 'dazed and confused' look about her, where Motoko always appears  (even in her moments of severe angst) sharp and focused. Batou in this clip looks comedic. I do hope the Tachikomas make an appearance, along with, maybe one of those HAW tanks.  Bottom line is, I didn't make this movie. I just hope they keep it intelligent, tight, fun, and that it succeeds in bringing credit to the GIS franchise.

text: The trailer did not capture the tone of the film. They should have reprised the opening choir of the Ghost in the Shell movie with silent background images until they talk... not some 80's nostalgia go-to. It would have been different. It would have the fans exploding. It would turn the heads of cynical reviewers.  The original content material is dark. It touches the gray area of what is and is not human. There is a reason the original's opening scene is of the main character being made from a mannequin robot. We will see how much the production company makes this controversial subject matter "safe" for public viewing.

text: Look i understand everyone has made the argument that Motoko isn't asian, that her model is ethnically ambiguous, Japan is okay with it, that ScarJo is perfect for the role simply because she's ScarJo, or that she looks white in the anime. But hear me out plz lol  1. Argument: Motoko's supposedly isn't asian because "the creators" didn't intend for her to be a certain ethnicity and that she's ethnically ambiguous.  Rebuttal: okay just because someone is described as "ethnically ambiguous" doesn't equal white. Her name is Motoko Kusanagi or as some ppl say is her alias, but that is her name nonetheless. No one knows her past and that leaves it up to interpretation and creative freedom. SO getting an asian actress like Rinko Kikuchi (Pacific Rim) isn't far fetched. She would've been a way better casting choice in my opinion than ScarJo. This story is a very Japanese one as it deals with Japan's close association with technology and how far ur humanity goes when ur fully cybernated. also they are deliberately not straying away from the asian aesthetic. If her model is supposed to be western then how the hell is she supposed to blend in looking whiter than a snowflake?  2. Argument: Japan is okay with it.  Rebuttal: This isn't a valid argument because it's like asking how Africans feel about racism towards African-Americans in America. Their answer wouldn't have the same perspective as African-Americans. Japan, a country where there isn't much immigration and they really try not to and where they have a homogeneous society, where if a Japanese person in Japan turns on their tv what do they see? more Japanese ppl. Japanese ppl don't really understand the concept of racism or whitewashing because they never had to deal with it. we (the us) have one of the most diverse populations in the world and hollywood obviously doesn't get it. they think casting the supporting cast with different ethnic groups checks off the diversity requirement and reserving the lead role for a white actor is ideal. I mean the guy playing Ishikawa is Australian! What the hell? im sorry. we have the diversity that other parts of the world don't and its about time Hollywood started using that and representing that properly. Its also kind of sad because guess what? ppl outside the us, sees the face of America as white. so who else would they expect to fill the roles of an American Ghost in The Shell? And its sucks.  3. Argument: ScarJo is perfect because its ScarJo and she make da money.  Rebuttal: The star power myth isn't really true. nobody knew chris hemsworth before thor, nobody knew jennifer lawrence before hunger games, nobody knew Rinko Kikuchi or Charlie Hunnam before Pacific Rim, nobody knew Henry Cavill before Man of Steel or Immortals, nobody knew Aaron Taylor before Kick Ass, nobody knew any of the ppl in the Last Airbender movie (i know it was bad) but that's the point....shall I go on? Ppl are going to see the ghost in the shell simply because its ghost in the shell not because of ScarJo. And secret: "not everyone likes ScarJo".  4. Argument: She looks white in the anime.  Rebuttal: have any of u seen anime? By that argument then everyone looks white! The key is that animated characters are perceived to be how u want them to be. How do u know if the Simpsons are about a white family? they're yellow. i could make the argument that they look canadian or latino for all we know. just because they look white to u doesn't mean they are. Also if u watch Anime they deliberately makes it clear to u that someone is foreign: blonde hair, blue eyes, telling u they're mixed, and also a funny accent when speaking Japanese.

text: For the people saying "they never specified her ethnicity" and "she's a cyborg"..  I wouldn't think you would need to specify ethnicity in an ANIME/MANGA,  especially when her name is "Motoko Kusanagi" and it takes place in JAPAN  (a place which 98% of people are indeed Japanese). In fact when they do specify ethnicity or race in an anime it's usually to let the audience know that they AREN'T of Japanese descent.   ***Most importantly to end this debate, she was supposed to be a generic looking model made to look inconspicuous and be able to blend into crowds so WHY WOULD SHE NOT BE MADE TO LOOK LIKE ALL THE OTHER JAPANESE PEOPLE IN THE CROWD??!?!?!?!  Would it really kill Hollywood to let an Asian-American play a lead role in a big film? When was the last time you saw an Asian play a lead role in a big American film (that wasn't a martial arts movie). People aren't "fake mad" just because of this role but at the fact that Asian-Americans are widely underrepresented in American film.  We all know they are casting a white person with a brand name to increase box office gross, which is understandable because at the end of the day money drives the world, but let's not pretend it's not white-washing. I'm not trying to start an argument so if you disagree, fine, but these excuses i've heard are pretty ridiculous.

text: I don't understand why people want the same thing as the books, original animes/cartoons, etc. I prefer a director to deviate a bit so that their take isn't like the original story made by someone else. That's their story work. If I wanted to read/watch the same thing I'd go back to the original every time. Its just silly to make a remake where you know every little detail. Let the director's tweak and change things so I can see their take on it.  When a music artist comes out with a song, another person makes a remix and uploads it on media like soundcloud or newgrounds that sounds similar but very different. Thats exactly how a director should act. People get so up tight in their tiny assholes about perfect adaptions of an original work. I just don't find paying for something I've already seen worth my time. Tweak it and tweak it liberally.

Gotta say, ScarJo's very stolid acting kinda fits the character from the 1995 animated movie (which is really different from the original manga character). So it was a bargain on the producer's side, you know. It's also part of the success of a movie, I guess. text: To what I see in the trailer they clearly missed the point what Masamune Shirow wanted to show in Ghost in the Shell. It looks like a typical holywood  action movie set in the future, with some kind of "they stole your identity" or "bad guys are actually good" plot twist, while the actual story of Ghost in the shell is about the definition  of having a soul (=Ghost) in an artificial body (=Shell) the contradiction in opposite manners and the value of a body (artificial or biological) to its soul or vice versa. Thats why its called: Ghost (your soul) in the Shell (the body). It goes far beyond some shooting scene and future backgrounds.   The trailer gives me the impression, that they poorly executed the plot from the original story and simply took the settings to advertise their movie creating something for the "mass". Yet again I do not think the movie has to be bad. Moreover I would say that the movie should not be called Ghost in the Shell  (as far my assumptions are correct) but simply "inspired" by what Masamune did. It deserve it`s own name, so it will not leave a bad aftertaste either, like the implementation of the Dragon Ball movie.

text: They pretty much changed the plot big time and totally lost the main "plot" of Ghost in the Shell (Ghost in the Machine -Arthur Koestler). The story was never about Kusanagi Motoko being a first of her kind. And it was also never about her trying to find her true identity because she already knew who she was. Also looking at the Trailer, they seem to have mashed up action scenes from both the 1995 Movie, and the TV series GITS:Stand Alone Complex (The intro where she jumped off from 1995 GITS and the android dolls taking diners as hostages from GITS Stand Alone Complex)... I highly doubt this live action can be as good as the Animation movies/series. If anything perhaps 20%-30% as good. The feel of the show (base on the trailer) is also dead since they started using their over sponsored shit music and not the one's Gabriela Robin uses (a.k.a. Yoko Kanno).  The main issue with creating a live action of an Animation such as Ghost in the Shell that have spawned several Movies, OVA's and Series that are very successful on their own is that the Bar was set very high by the Animations alone which is hard to beat. Specially harder to beat when you make a live action that have a big change in plot, mis-cast the characters and many more.  Unlike an example..  the  Manga and Novel "All you need is kill" it was a Manga and Novel that was not as well known as Ghost in the Shell, it was not animated even.. It was easy to make a movie out of it and become successful Without so much critics cause it was relatively not well known to many manga and Novel readers (I have read thousand's of manga titles  and I never heard of that manga until I finished watching Edge of Tomorrow.. that's how relatively Unknown that manga really is...). The "Manga and Novel All you Need is kill" = Live action movie is called "Edge of Tomorrow/Live-Die-Repeat".  But ye, for this Movie to be successful. They have to produce something that can be on par or overpass the quality the 1995 movie possess (but I don't think they can...) Unlike Edge of Tomorrow which proved to be very successful.   Even Edge of Tomorrow did not 100% Follow the "All You Need is Kill" Manga and Novel faithfully, it had a heavily westernised casting, and a lot of things were changed in the story. But it was successful nonetheless cause that particular manga and Novel was not that well known/mainstream unlike Ghost in the Shell which is more popular and have high scores on the Animated Movie and Series (which this live action movie have to beat or say atleast get 50% as good). Either its going to be a flop or its the typical Hollywood Influence thing where it only gained huge box office cause a lot of people watched it = Mostly people who have no idea what Ghost in the Shell is and have yet to watch the Ghost in the Shell 1995 or the Series (Ghost in the Shell Stand Alone Complex Season 1 and 2, GITS:Innocence and many more).  I would say, if you plan on watching this live action, go watch the Ghost in the Shell 1995 atleast and perhaps Ghost in the Shell Stand Alone Complex Season 1 and 2 as well. And then Watch this trailer again. See the huge difference. (Just saying :P).

text: I sincerely hope that the details and the premise of the anime are upheld in this remake. The original film detailed some interesting revelations about the interface between humans and machines. Cybernetics, and consciousness, the defining characteristics on that field being moral dilemmas, and whose ultimate responsibility it was, the unsettling answer being that no one or thing knew.   That's what made this film, and the subsequent series so comforting to watch, as, such issues are present today, in our everyday lives, yet we are unable to observe their effects on us as a beings living out of our mental projections, only within the mental framework of a dystopian future are we able to pick objectively at our own immortality. The answer once again, being that noone or thing has control, and this idea is made all the more startling when observed in the mind of a machine.   The ideas behind the movie reference many an important philosophy, but, I think scientifically, as we stand today, theoretical neuroscience (a ways forward) and its understanding of the mind as a, ultimately, and, as far as the main points about it go, a learning machine, that, can, become a caveat for any who look nonchalantly at a humble stone axe made millennia ago by a bird, and objectively rely on the idea of a non-sentient accumulation at work. Because well simply, the mind of a machine is in the CPU right? well, you say, no, that's the brain. Then, dare I ask, what is the mind?

text: This is going to suck, and nobody's pointing out the reason why; they're making it _about_ Motoko Kusanagi.  What made GitS great was that it was about two things: the philosophical and political ramifications of a world in which most people are cyberized (their nanomachine-infused brains are connected directly to the internet).  It tackled questions of identity, rights, and the ship of Theseus, while deconstructing the setting with brain-hacking counterterrorists solving cyber-crimes.  Any information we learned about Motoko along the way was _incidental_ because *THE STORY ISN'T ABOUT HER.*  Making it about her uncovering her past, and throwing in these cheesy one-liners, is Hollywood bullshit that is painting a great franchise into nothing more than "Kill Bill meets Robocop."

text: Problem being, GITS was a very, well, intellectual series, that dealt with a lot of theoretical issues regarding trans-humanism, artificial intelligence, and societal changes in the wake of large scale cyber-ization. And from the looks of the trailer, they've done the usual "person with powers finding out her hidden past" spiel that's been done to death before. I'm sure the movie will LOOK great, SOUND great, and (hopefully) have a coherent plot, but this trailer gives off none of the 'feel', the 'soul' that Ghost had in almost all of its previous incarnations. Also, Batou doesn't look like Batou at all, haha, where's my old grizzled war vet!

text: I've never seen people get this upset over ''whitewashing'' in hollywood before. If you really think there's some racist conspiracy to keep non-white actors out of movies you're an idiot. Movie studios only care about money, so they'll chose a well-known white actress over an unknown Asian actress any day. NOT because they hate asians, but because they're selling a movie to a western market and there aren't very many well known Asian actors to begin with, mostly because they make up such a small percentage of the US population. I know it's easy to yell ''RACISM'' every time something like this happens, but next time maybe actually consider there are tons of factors that can influence casting choices.

text: If you prefer the anime and manga so much just go watch/read them. They haven't gone anywhere. Personally I like the direction they are going with this. I don't want it to be the same as the series or the animated movie, I want it to be unpredictable and for it to bring new food for thought to the table. That's what Ghost in the Shell is and always has been, thought provoking and raising potential issues in future society. Surely you'd be disappointed if it was the same concepts explored again and again. Try to remember guys that this may be someone's first look at the GITS universe and could spur more writers to explore it in new and interesting ways whilst broadening the audience, that's got to excite you; potentially having more people to talk to about this amazing story.

text: At first I was very sketchy about this movie. Another Japanese classic tarnished by American Hollywood. But, I am pleased to say that this movie looks like it's going to be really good. I like Scarlett Johansson. I believe she does a great job in the films she has been in. I think the only two that would have placed in my mind that this one wouldn't make it were Under the Skin & Lucy. But, I always have to remind myself that I can't judge an actor/actresses' performance solely on them; because they are led by a director. And that 1 or 2 flops (in my eyes) doesn't speak for that person's entire career. Overall, I am really looking forward to this movie and what Hollywood and the actors can bring to the table. Please, don't let me down.

text: I think a lot of people are missing the point here and just fixating on the casting. Who cares. I just want someone who can play the role and understands the Major's proper lack of emotion and reasoning thereof; so seeing the Major crack a one-liner and slyly smile afterwards is already off-putting (not that GitS doesn't have some level of humor). Personally, the shape of Scar-Jo's face and the way that she acts, she shows emotion whether she means to or not. Can she step up? Maybe, hopefully. We all want a good movie so all we can do is hope that she can. I don't care what ethnicity that entails as long as they view the source material and do it right. Instead, as it's a Hollywood movie that has to explain a ton of things to not alienate non-GitS viewers, shouldn't we be more concerned that introducing, understanding and coming to a conclusion in a two-hour film surrounding the complexity of the GitS universe is going to be one hell of an tough-to-achieve task?

text: Strangely, I'm finding Johanssons' voice really disturbing in this.   I like Johansson, but after years of GITS, SAC, etc, I'm too used to strong voice actresses playing the part. The major has a strong, clear voice which nicely represents her cool self-assuredness and military experience. Put simply, The Major is a bad ass. She has the voice of a military commander...  Johanssons' breathy whispering here just conveys doubt and uncertainty. I understand she's probably trying to convey exactly that, since she is going through a sort of existential crisis here, but its just out of character. Even when Kusanagi was at her most self-doubting phase, questioning the existence of ghost, she never sounded this wishy-washy. She attacked it like just another intellectual problem while tossing back a beer.

text: Everything looks beautiful and the acting is great, but only one thing has partly ruined this adaptation for me and that's the sensitivity and soft tone of voice that Scarlett Johansson has. She has too much of a soft voice and mellow personality to suit Motoko Kusanagi. Motoko has a very wild and strong personality, also her eyes defined her greatly. Motoko's death stare and serious expression were one of the characteristics that defined her as a very unique character in the cyberpunk era and Scarlett doesn't seem like she will be delivering that to us. Trembling while holding a gun?! I know it's an adaptation of the puppet master but watch the Sniper episode with Pazu and Motoko in Stand Alone Complex.... that's my interpretation of the original Motoko!  It's such a bummer....

text: Looks good.  And there goes random screw ups big and small: - Cliche "wall running"... Also the second guy brave heroine shoots while "wall running" should've emptied like half of the magazine right in her wherever really, but screenwriters saved the day. - "You were dying - we saved you" cliche crap. - WTF with "you are the first of your kind"!? In "source materials" - she got her full synth body when she was just a kid and by the time it happened, this sort of practice was already relatively common. And here you're trying to pitch it as if we're watching RoboCop. Also "one of a kind" cliche... - 1:25 - I'd start blaming screenwriters - Chief Aramaki took a gun in his hands like once in whole Ghost In The Shell animated movie/series and/or manga universes and here he takes out a death squad with just 6 shots... But it's Takeshi Kitano - what else would you expect?... - 1:30 - I'll just assume that you forgot to add the "eye implants" for Bato's character there. Also I got the feeling - somebody forgot about the fact that he has full synthetic body just like Major Kusanagi does. - 1:34 - and that's where Motoko's motivation goes out of the window, right into hollywoods graveyard of cliche motivations. - 1:48 - Ok. That's just sad. I really hope that guy was  not "The Laughing Man" character. Also another grave stone on hollywood cliche hero origins graveyard.

text: 1) Looks creative. 2) The trailer smells of fear from the producers. They're trying too hard. It's like "hey teen boys... look she's naked and kissing another girl... buy a damn ticket!" While at the same time trying too hard to show iconic scenes from the original.  3) The original is one of my all time favorite anime. It was almost profetic in describing social media and how we will interact in the future. Major is a character that lets you explore that world. This however feels (at least the trailer made it seem that way) that her past will be an important plot point. That feels a little too clich√© and overdone, whereas the original was more about exploring a future world and what it means to be alive.  4) This is not to say the movie doesn't look appealing or that I'm not looking forward to it. I'm just saying from the trailer it looks like the makers are too focused on it's success and targeting audiences that I get a feel like some of what made the anime fun might be lost. Again obviously it's all speculation.  5) Best I can say about it is the look and SJH seems alright in the role.
