The biggest red flag for me has nothing to do with Scarlett playing the Major(Lets make it straight as well that she never calls herself the Major but Kusanagi) but its the visuals, visuals play a HUGE role in movies and they shot themselves in the foot, the background is sooo distracting, and you can make the argument they did it to draw in the audience but to me as someone who's a avid fan its painful. Also the Major is not the first full body prosthetic. As a matter of fact there are several of them even in the first movie.  Note: This part was made after watching the trailer.  The Major knows who she is! She didn't lose her past, theres a bit about becasue she lost her original body she feels like she's lost her original ghost but thats it. Ugh I hate movie trailers like this.  One last note before I wrap up. Batou! No! He's ghastly!  I hope the best for this movie, and its going to make its money, what I hope is that it'll get people watching the original Ghost in the Shell.

text: Extremely disappointed with this. At first I got quite hyped with the visual but then I heard the premisse for the Major's character: "I'm looking for who I am", "I'm insecure, I don't know who to trust". This sounded ridiculously shallow and cheesy. Really hope there is more depth to that.    They could have gone for many different approaches for the Major;   Oshii's: A dark slightly depressed but deep intelectual and introspective woman, clearly detached from her humanity but still with desires to dive deep into the mysteries of the new world she lives in and the nature of life.   Shirow's Original Major: A tough "gorila babe" with a sarcastic but wit sense of humor that fights for justice and has a difficult time getting herself a strong man that can handle her, so she still has some lesbian fun with some youger friends of hers. Much more like a young tough but humorous "female detective".   Or Kamiyama's Major: Kinda of a mix of the two, a mysterious extremely intelligent and talented character with a little bit of sarcasm spiced with no problem in showing her sexiness, still she wonders about the nature of the ghosts and her own identity but in her own mature adult away.  All three Majors share a common trait: She is a strong independent woman. THE LAST THING I'D EXPECT TO SEE IN MAJOR IS INSECURITY! Her identity crisis is that more of a mid aged woman, definetely NOT of an endgy insecure teenager.   That seems like a really shallow generic main character. Seems to me hollywood still can't take Japanese animation (and manga) seriously enough. This is not catering to the adult audience fan of GITS that first saw this back in the late nights, but to dumb millennium teenagers.

text: The movie looks pretty good. The visuals of the city landscapes look fantastic! I know a lot of people complain that the major isn't being played by an Asian, but honestly, all ethnicity aside, Scarlet Johansson does seem like the right kind of person to play the major. Besides, one of the hole ideas from the original anime was that her character wasn't in her original body, but rather in a mass-produced assembly line body built by a big corporation, so I think it could still work with having Scarlet Johansson playing her, in terms of story and what not. The biggest thing that I don't like in this trailer is how Batou looks. He was one of my favorite characters from the original anime(in particular, the second anime film "inesense"). I like the guy they got to play him, but His eye lenses are way too small and just look kind of weird the way they did them. Also there were some scenes where he had normal looking eyes in the trailer, which he never had in any of the anime versions. Hopefully the rest of the movie is adapted pretty faithfully. I looked up the "shelling sequence" scene which they did for this movie and it looked amazing! It was about as perfect as they could have adapted that scene. They even had the same music from the anime film. So I don't know. Hopefully this will be a good film. I'll defiantly see it when it comes out.

text: Although I do understand the disdain for Ghost In the Shell having an  Non-Asian lead, I do feel those who choose to not see the film will  ultimately hinder Asian actor's ability to get better roles. The very  fact that we are going to see a classic Anime live action adaptation in  less than three months is ground breaking. Anime has fought hard to make  its way into pop culture. I remember visiting my local mall's Sundance  store. It was the only store that carried Anime. I also remember  becoming hooked on films like Ghost in the Shell, Akira, Venus Wars, and  Ninja Scroll. I found these films because some one chose to mention  them in a magazine or some other form of media I was into at the time.  And although I was too young to appreciate them fully, I became a fan.  Now fast forward to 2017 and we have a 150 million dollar adaptation of  one of these classics of the 90s. It's progress. It may not be 100% what  we want but its a start. If Anime are to be celebrated by the masses  you need to have mass appeal. Charlotte brings that to the table. No one  who is not a Geek of Anime or movies knows what this movie is. What  will bring them to theaters is their interest in the trailer and the  lead actress. If we can get them watching, then we can then more live  action Anime. And if we introduce more Anime we can begin casting more  Asian actors into the roles. Marvel is in the process of bringing comics  to the main stream in the same fashion. Who ever thought we would see  so many characters brought to life on the big screen. We have mainstream  audiences to thank for that, not just the enthusiast. One day I hope  comics will be considered accessible by everyone. And I also hope that  of Anime. So, I beg you, if you are fan of Anime please see this film.  The more people who do, the more reasons to make other adaptations.  Boycotting the movie will cause more harm than good. So GO SEE Ghost In  The Shell! :)

The philosohy doesn't always revolve around the Major, nor does the fact that the Major seems vurnrable, or always confused about her past. In the 1995 movie, she wonders how much of her humanity is stripped away, and how much of a robot she is. It's not like she has amnesia in the original movie, nor is wonderd who she really is. she doesn't really care, she wonders how much of her is left. She never had her life stolen or whatever. She was rescued and she chose to join the police force. Oh and she's Japanese. Kuze is Japanese too. Watch 2nd GIG.

text: Same comments over and over again here...Look, name me ONE Japanese actress if you're in the U.S. Go. Couldn't think of one, could you? Right. And if you could, guess what? She's not a Hollywood A-lister. She's not even a "D Lister" (maybe that girl from Memoirs of a Geisha, let's say...). Fanboys may go to see a movie because its adapted from something they love. Everyone else goes to see one movie over another because they like the actor/director, the trailer looks good, or it got good reviews. Scarlett Johansson has proven her top billing status and acting ability. That's why she was chosen for the role. If the only people that go see this movie are fanboys, it won't make enough for them to make another movie like this one. And if you look at the how the character looks in the anime, she looks just like her.   Making Shredder from TMNT William Fichner, I could understand those complaints because it completely changed the story. But this, c'mon. You're just looking for something to complain about, and while you do so, you make filmmakers afraid to take risks and deviate from the source material. Meanwhile, most of you can't create your way out of a paper bag. You just excel at complaining.

text: +Gordon Graham "There are white Japanese now, and not just a few of them." Yes there are just a few of them. All research I ever read on the subject points to single-digit percentages of recent non-Japanese ancestry among the Japanese population, and of those, the majority are actually Asian (e.g. Korean, Chinese, Filipino etc.) Anecdotally, when I lived in Japan, the number of 'white' people in most locales was... well I was usually the only one. Of course you are going to meet many at cultural centers or events which specifically cater to Western-descended people, as did I - but that is hardly representative of the whole.  A movie set in *modern-day* Japan where all the main characters are white would rightfully be laughed/booed out of the room for being terribly whitewashed as well as preposterous. No one would swallow the excuse that in the novel of manga source set in 2016 Tokyo it wasn't specified that the characters weren't all white, so they just might be all white. It would be ridiculous in how unrepresentative it is. This GitS movie gets away with it (or rather the makers think it will) because the near future setting gives them a flimsy BS excuse, that's all.

text: Most actions scenes seem to be right out of the original anime (1995) which I'm happy to see. But what I'm really interested in is if the plot will sort of fix the lose ends that the anime had. They were minor and practically didn't take away from the experience, but they were there. As for the whole 'discovering who I am' stuff, I don't know how that fits. I mean it was never fully clear if Major merged with the Puppeteer or not in the 1995 anime, but she knew who she was and what she lacked. Maybe they'll use the merge part (if it's in the movie) to tie in the 'discovery' plot. That is if there is a Puppeteer as the main villain and not the company who created her. (Which now thing about it, created the villain as well). Because of that they could make Major and the villain friend/enemies, but I don't know how I feel about that since they were never on the same side. The visuals are beautiful though and I"m liking how they stayed with her 'naked' costume. Sure a bit more white, but it seems to work, at least in the trailer. Here's hoping its actually good, because both anime and manga were awesome! (Just as an off note I'm referencing things based solely on the 1995 anime, so if things were explained in the original manga or the TV show, I wouldn't know since I haven't read/seen those.)
author: Brenda Correa

text: This may be all style and little substance. May be destined for the $3.99 bin at Best Buy. They are trying to make a niche movie into a mainstream movie meaning a dumbed down version with big stars, explosions, and too much slo mo. I think this idea would have come off better under a foreign studio which would focus more on the story and less on trying to make it a blockbuster. Now that Marvel and DC are starting to cool off, live action anime might be the new flavor. I also don't think Akira will come off well as a live action feature because of the fact that it is the art and not its bloated story that makes Akira stand out. When you talk to anyone about Akira, they talk about the animation, not the story. What makes anime like these great is the fact that they don't look real, but are extremely well drawn. It's this distance that makes them appealing. Live action will take away from the art and draw more attention to the story which is not bad if the stories are well written. But looking at how much money went into the look of this trailer I doubt that it's counterbalanced with a well written script. This may go the way of Aeon Flux when all is said and done,

text: "No no no, bad bad bad, wrong wrong wrong."  I enjoy Miss Johansson as an actress but the Major is Japanese. So are Batou, Chief Aramaki, Togusa, Ichikawa and the Tachikoma. The setting is high-tech but there are many episodes that clearly state that the country is Japan. The relationship between technology and Section 9 is Japanese in a time when Japan was cutting-edge of the entire technological market. The Internet was a scary place in 1995 and the concept of the hackers was new and frightening. The manga debuted in 1989.   The Japanese name of this show is not "Busty Skin-Suit Heroine". It's "Mobile Armored Riot Police" and the Major heads up an elite police squad that even has trouble staying active among the legitimate police squad and military. They're the elite of the elite (Batou's an ex-ranger) and that's why they can afford cybernetic prosthetic upgrades. Section 9 willfully signs away their professional lives and all their time and the enhancements are a free perk for the commitment. Otherwise they're next to impossible to maintain. There is no amnesia plot in the series. Section 9 tracks Laughing Man in season one and handles Comrade Kuze in season two.  Go on KissAnime and watch the 1995 animated film (dubbed or subbed) before you say anything positive about this tripe. Kusanagi faces and merges with a superhacker and never gains amnesia. I couldn't even sit through this trailer. I stopped it after 36 seconds because seeing Miss Johansson in that outfit makes me want to claw out my eyes. Not only is she not Japanese; she is not Major Kusanagi.

text: People here are complaining about the looks and ethnicity of the main character. I'm more wondering about whether the content of the film will be just as good and intriguing. The trailer gives more of a crime action vibe than a psychological thriller and philosophical one. Though I do like how they've done the cyberpunk aspect in this.  The philosophy behind the original film was among the best aspects of it for me. The questions raised, the self-reflection and the deep discussions that took place. So many great things about the original and i'm more so wondering how they will carry it out in the film and whether it'll be as interesting, deep and thought provocative. So i'll reserve judgement until after i've seen it, otherwise i'm more cautious about it appearing more action-like than anything. But then again trailers are known to do that with films like this.

text: I've been hearing a lot of negatives on this movie because they got Scarlett Johansson to play the main character instead of an Asian woman. They are calling it white washing. Look, I know that there are some shameful/disgusting ignoring/disrespect of ethnicity that goes on in Hollywood like having a predominantly white cast for movies of Egypt (a place in Africa) and other things like that, but I have to say that I don't see it here. The main character on the Ghost in the Shell anime actually looks more like Scarlett Johansson than any Asian woman I've seen. It is not like in something like Exodus: Gods and Kings or Gods of Egypt. And I am not an anime fan or anything, but a lot of the anime characters look nothing like people we consider Asian. It'd be like if someone had a character named Lee Chin in an animated film and he was a tall man with dark brown, chocolate-like skin with a lean, muscular build. You can't really blame people for choosing Michael B. Jordan to play that character in a live action movie.

text: I dunno... while I recognize the scenes from the anime (like the fight in the water) I get the feeling it is nowhere near that. Like that "bad guy" reminds you hard of the hacker in the anime as well, but the story seems to be wayyy personal. I miss her cold analysing cyborg feel. Like in the anime you see a woman but it is pretty clear she ain't human. She lacks typical human behaviour because from a pure logical point of view it doesn't make sense to be like that. Lots of small things, like the facial expresion being mostly the same, not blinking, turning around with a mechanical movement, not as fluent as the human coworkers....   And I AM aware the manga also featured a more humanesque Motoko, giving ground for an argument about this movie being closer to the actual source (manga), but the anime cyborg was so, SO good. I would've loved her to be like that instead of this obvious human version. I mean even the plastic face geisha there is blinking... wtf. :\

text: The Major does not act in response to her body. Whatever actions she would react to would be the result of her mental capacities. With the introduction of a means for the mind to travel through the net.  Any potential for body and mind to be interwoven together indefinitely is destroyed. Following this train of thought we run into concepts that sum up descartes in it's entirety.   The very notion of ‚ÄúI think therefore I am‚Äù is the basis for Motoko‚Äôs reasoning. That she must be something however her reasoning takes it a step further.  Which denotes that memories are something that makes up an individual. So that while she may have artificial parts. She has memories that are unique to her.   While she seemingly has the free will of thought and decision. It is only given to her when she fulfills her purpose in the company. She aids in fighting criminal hackers within Section 9. But the moment she decides to give up fulfilling such a task she will be terminated. This also leads me full circle to the idea that our lives are shaped by death.   However the whole idea that Ghost in the Shell was a revenge story is a hack in itself. There no conspiracy theory here as it doesn't exist. That's just Hollywood's way of giving us the middle finger. Visually speaking the movie looks pretty good but that's about the only good thing I can say about it.

text: I saw it in theaters and it was amazing. The visuals and soundtrack were beautifully paired to create an atmospheric world. The deeper meanings were present and were more of an updated version of previous answers offered. The story is complex enough to stand above generic sci-fi films but not convoluted or confusing. The various symbolic undertones smoothly intertwine with the main story, creating a fascinating film. The film itself has less philosophy than the 1995 anime, but there is some present. The characters are not cardboard cutouts; they're developed and walk a blurred line between right and wrong and their motivations are complex. Scarlett Johansson was incredible as an actress in this role, and helps add emotional connection to the fleshed out Motoko Kusanagi character.  The only noticeable flaws were a with pacing and with a few simplistic dialogue moments. The trailer presented a more simplistic film than the film itself. Other than that, I say it's worthy of theater admission price.

text: I saw this today and it was fuckin awesome. Totally payed respect to the original anime so for the idiots who just felt this need to boycott it because of this "whitewash" crap or whatever you call it, you missed out on a great movie. You missed out on a great movie because of your pettiness and inability to just focus on the movie rather than the color of the skin of the lead actress, ScarJo was awesome as Major btw and the perfect choice to play her. People have been doing this for years and it's not just "whitewashing" as some would have you believe. Fanboys complained when Samuel L. Jackson was cast as Nick Fury when he's white in the comics and they complained when Will Smith, another black man was cast as Deadshot. Both Samuel L. Jackson and Will Smith were great in the roles and I could care less about the color of their skin. Scarlett was great here too as the major but because the color of her skin wasn't quite right for fanboys they stupidly ignored it and missed out. I couldn't care less what the color of your skin is, if you're good in the role then that's all I need and Scarlett Johansson was damn good in the role. This whitewashing crap and complaining about a characters skin, including Jackson and Smith, in every movie actually contributes more to racism in this country because doing stuff like bitching about the characters skin color brings racism to the forefront again when we're trying to all be equal. People are so stupid that they don't even realize that in Ghost in the Shell it's just a body, it's just a shell, the girl, the soul is an Asian girl which the new movie explained. People need to just get over shit sometimes and just enjoy a good movie because I guarantee all of you morons who wanna "boycott" ghost in the shell because of "whitewashing" as soon as you see this movie someday whether it be on Blu Ray or just on TV someday you'll realize how ignorant you were for ignoring this movie for such a petty stupid reason. Once you see this movie someday you'll realize what a mistake you made

text: It wasn't very good honestly. There were things it did well and some recreated scenes from the original were done pretty well BUT the context is completely screwed up so the scenes don't work as well. And yeah, it's taken away a lot of the thought provoking themes of the original. I'll say this though, it's the best live action Hollywood film based on an anime so far. I mean, look at things like Dragon Ball Evolution and Speed Racer, this is clearly a better product than those. But it's still not great. This was a risky movie for them to make because outside of the anime community, Ghost in the Shell wasn't exactly a popular source for them to remake. It's just a shame they focused on the less important parts of the story.    And I'm choosing not to comment on the whole white Major thing.

text: I don't agree with the explicit internal dialogue concerning her origin.  In the OVA it was implied that Motoko was basically a human consciousness in a mechanical body. How she got there was never explored in the OVA.  I do love their adherence to some of the key scenes.  But I do not understand why they haven't mentioned the puppetmaster (project 2501) in the trailer so that makes me question how much does this movie follow the OVA? How much creative freedom was taken with this film?  The best parts of the OVA were questions about what makes an AI sentient, what makes a human human, can a machine have a spirit, Motoko's journey through her own existence and her ultimate conclusion, etc.  I feel like most of that might not be in this film.  I can't wait to see it, don't get me wrong but of all the adaptations and reboots that I've seen this one causes me the most anxiety and its strange.

text: Having seen the movie I am actually okay with how it was written it stands as a decent movie (50-60 tomatoes).  Some elements felt like a prequel which I found interesting but should not have been a main story point.  I understand the obsession with origin stories but they had not established GiTS on film so I think it was a little too hollywood to try to build in context for the major like that.  They retained enough of the OVA to use the title but I believe they can do better and totally expect a reboot in the next few years (like they did with "The Hulk" vs "The Incredible Hulk", for example).  Some movies don't need it (like Total Recall, which was perfectly cheesy, although I'll never turn down Kate Beckinsale on any medium)  Did the producers and director think that the public wouldn't relate to this movie without some kind of love story?  Did they need to humanize the Major so much?  Subtlety is lost on this production.  They should have allowed some interpretation.  It's okay to have "Rosebud" elements to provoke thought in the audience.  Part of the charm of GiTS was that you wouldn't relate to it by default. Sci-Fi is meant to explore the futuristic and surreal potential of humanity.  See anything written by Asimov or Clarke.  We deserve thought provoking movies that don't try to fill in all the blanks for us.  There are no unanswered questions in this film and that is disappointing.  Actually, it would have benefited from a lower budget.

text: lil opinion from me. i watched the movie. i watched the anime.  soo i can say kinda tell em apart.  the movie is actually REALLY well done. its something that bashes away the audience with an experience they actually put to good use.  sure, hollywood ruined some anime's BUT this one? its actually VERY well done.  Scarlett Johansson is in my opinion a very good fitting person for the role. at first i was scared the movie would ruin it. but no it actually didnt.  sure the movie played with the original GitS story. but it wasnt horrible.  *** SPOILERS!!!! SKIP IF YOU DONT WANT TO READ IT ****  the anime ends up with major getting onto the net, and gets out of her body. she helps batou in the second anime movie with the puppet master. not gonna tell more about it.  the Hollywood version ends up with a diffirent ending! she.. shit well i said spoilers! she ends up alive and keeps going with her team. she lives and the ''puppet master'' aka in this movie one of the test subjects for a ''ghost in the shell''.  **** SPOILERS ENDED****  NOW! what can i say? the hollywood version is a little dumbed down, sinds it does explain a LOT, of the story in a good way. its a great movie imo.  The anime, is really for ppl who know anime's throughout. in the sense of understanding a storyline without knowing it, searching the puzzles pieces yourself. anyway.  conclusion. watch the movie, both of em.  i recommend it. for ppl who never watched anime, watch the movie ghost in the shell first, soo you know the start of the story a little. BEWARE! the anime is diffirent! soo dont say its bad, its diffirent.  now, have fun watching both of em. for anime lovers: really guys, no worries, i wasnt liking the whitewashed idea either, but i gave it a try and wham.  it was good.  just lets hope they wont milk it out like the usual movies they bring out.. *cough cough* super hero movies, Fast and the Furious *cough cough*  ya had fun reading it? sweet. ya didnt liked it? well sorry i wasnt entertaining enough... go to the kitchen and grab a cookie.

text: I think it's about time Scarlett Johansson showed us her acting chops if she has any. This is yet another role where she jumps around and acts dumb and she is beginning typecast herself with superhero /sci-fi roles. I would love to see her do something with a little substance, . Ghost in the Shell is set in the future in which humans and technology have begun to merge, a cybernetically enhanced soldier hunts a mysterious terrorist who can hack into his victims' minds and control their thoughts and memories. Her pursuit eventually leads her to discover the full truth about her past.I wasn't surprised to read Ghost in the Shell was adapted from a Japanese Manga series from the 80's as it has that fantastical feel about it. Fantastical not fantastic. It also has the feel of a video game which is perhaps why it didn't do too much for me. The first 45 minutes bored me silly but thankfully the last hour was much better. Good special affects and fine performance from underrated actor Pilou Asb√¶k still won't have me queuing up for any more in what is quite obviously going to be a new franchise. 6 out of 10

text: The biggest issue I had with the movie was the lack of the Puppet Master and the philosophy of our point of existing as in the original. All we got from this movie was "Memories don't define you." Okay, cool. What happened to the, "What is consciousness? Who are we to say a being or species is not conscious or self aware when it would be so hard for another species or being to figure out that we are. Why are we self-aware? Is there meaning to it or accidental? Is reproduction our way of immortality? But passing on our genetic pool as far as that bloodline will take us? Is a part of our consciousness put into each person we 'create'? Are we all one single consciousness that has branched out since the beginning of mankind?" I was really hoping, with this movie reaching such a wider audience, that it would use something at least similar to the Puppet Master's speech to try and turn that little switch on in people's brains. One that makes people possibly more self aware than they want to be for that moment in time. I remember the speech so much from the original that I saw when I was 16, and it had such an impact on me. It made me take a step back at the bigger picture on a nearly daily basis. Which is honestly a bit scary but I do wish more people did it. It's such a shame they didn't stick to the puppet master and bring the same philosophy into it that made the original such a classic to begin with.

text: Got bored during break: **First 7 minutes of the ghost in the shell movie. ** -- " Deus Ex 3 synth music 'Bwaahs' " Stop doing this...... 100% of post-2009 scifi movies don't need 100% identical synth music. - Generic amnesia plot for the first dialogue in the entire movie. Was this written by the emo in the back of highschool algebra class or something?  **edit:**  Yup.  The ugly forgettable deus ex "bwaa" music goes on for 21 minutes . . . . oh and deleted some bullet points because they are selfish xD  --31 minutes in: " Hack this, hack that, he's being hacked, that's being hacked, hacked hacked hacked " Don't insult your audience by dumbing down everything into leymans-terms  xD  I will say though. I am loving the 'bro'mance between the major and batou though. lol  Guess that's one of the perks of being the director//writer. Do whatever the hell you want and it's awesome ‚ô•  It's really strange though. It's like the first 20 minutes of this movie are directed differently(probably for that "first 5 minutes" trailer) and it really tries to put you off from sticking around to watch the rest of it, but _its like that one asteroid movie_ where the people get better at playing their parts later in the movie. It's really fun to see how horrible the first chapter of the movie is compared to the final 30 minutes, and even the music direction is different. (p.s. sadly, nothing like this trailer music, which is absent. making the trailer theme of this upload total bullshit)  The big problem with this movie is that it tries to make everything uncanny instead of just letting go of the source material and replacing the more outlandish stuff with what will work _in real life_. The yellow-spandex effect and "YourCostumeNeedsWork" tropes in full effect. If you can't go for the fancy noir undertones and jazz pieces that the source materials liked using, try some other thematic setup. Just not  **the exact opposite** and this movie would've been way cooler  final edit: The amnesia thing I complained about... It's actually done pretty well. :D

I think the second half of the movie was alot better when it got into it's stride a bit more, i really liked the scenes with the major and her mother i thought they were done well, and that adds alot, as i think they did get over the major's feelings of lonilness quite well which gave these scenes more impact.  It's worth a watch, and you probably do get more out of it if you have some knowledge of the series going in, but it's nothing particularly groundbreaking as with most live action adaptations, so just set your expectations going in.

text: So why does her Shell look like a bodysuit? I thought Shells were supposed to look just like an organic body. I wouldn't mind seeing this as a simple design change, but it's so painfully obvious it was done to get a PG13 rating to rake in the most cash, because Americans are still afraid of nudity. The opening wasn't supposed to be an action sequence. It sets up the basics of the world, Section 6's militant structure (or is that section 9? Damn Manga's dub is confusing), the Major's job, and the abilities of a Shell. The story seems to have been altered drastically, with the Major being the first Ghost to have a Shell, but so many other things are kept the same. This just looks like as big as a disaster as Dragon Ball Evolution. I really hope anime producers stop licensing their properties to American film companies.

text: Just want to vent my emotions after watching it again so... Scarlett and all the other actors are the only good thing in this movie. The problem is just dumb script and dialogues which over-explain every banal thing but omit all the real stuff (probably it was too deep for the scriptwriters to read sum basic post-modern philosophy so they had to fill that hole with glorifying simple idea of individuality which was safer and commercially more feasible bet to keep the casual movie-goer and his uniqueness satisfied) Too much exposition of the world, killing all the mystery and subtlety and at the same time too much uselessly floating CGI's again added but for wrong reasons, ironically just to hide the emptiness of the world. Cartoon-like evil characters with obvious names, obtusive playing on feelings like every damn 5 minutes. I would cut first 5 minutes out of the movie completely. The intro unlike originals doesn't have any impact. Also the score is kinda bleak... aaand the biggest fail for me: Motoko Kusanagi was always just an alias not her real name so the justification for whitewashing was totaly unnecessarry. There!...... I feel better now.

text: SAW THIS IN THE THEATER....AND NOW RE-WATCHING IT ON DVD....IT'S ON PAUSE......THE 2ND VIEWING IS VERY IMPORTANT......IT WILL LET U KNOW IF U WERE RIGHT OR WRONG IN YOUR ASSESMENT OF THE FILM THE 1ST TIME AROUND....PLUS U CAN GET SOME EXTRA DETAILS THAT U WILL NATURALLY MISS THE 1ST TIME AROUND...MY FIRST IMPRESSION OF THIS FILM WAS..."SLIGHTLY DARK,INTRIGUING (in all of it's exsistential and philosophical implications),VISUALLY EPIC...(in it's ability to show a fantastic amalgamation and man and technology as one)...THRILLING,AND JUST BASICALLY A GREAT FILM EXPERIENCE....I BELIEVE I WAS ON THE EDGE OF MY SEAT THE WHOLE TIME....ALSO.....THIS FILM DOES SOMETHING WITH COLOR AND SOUND THAT IS AS BRILLIANT AND ADVANCED AS ANYTHING I'VE EVER SEEN FROM KUBRICK OR SPIELBERG OR WHOEVER...THE COLORS IN THIS FILM ARE MEANT TO MAKE U FEEL A CERTAIN WAY....THEY ARE USED TO GREAT EFFECT TO MAKE U BELIEVE IN THIS WORLD....SAME THING WITH THE SOUND...THE MUSIC IS A GODSEND,PERIOD....IT'S THE BEST....U COULD'NT ASK FOR MORE FITTING MUSIC FOR THIS KIND OF STORY...IT'S THE STRANGER THINGS SOUNDTRACK 100 YEARS IN THE FUTURE....THAT'S A COMPLIMENT....IT IS.....AND THE VISUALS,IT'S LIKE....THERE'S SO MUCH DETAIL IN THE VISUALS I'M JUST AMAZED...IT'S JUST LIKE IMAGINATION OVERLOAD....VERY,VERY AMBITIOUS...EVERY FRAME IS JUST ARTISTICALLY GORGEOUS...PACKED WITH COOL COLORS,MUSIC,SOUND FX AND IMAGERY....AND I DO BELIEVE AT TIMES THIS FILM CAN BECOME HEART-BREAKINGLY DEEP...WITH IT'S INTERESTING PHILOSOPHICAL IMPLICATIONS AND CIRCUMSTANCES........OK.....B4 I FINISH THIS MOVIE,LET ME SAY,I THINK THIS IS ONE OF THE BEST SCI-FI MOVIES EVER MADE....HANDS DOWN....LISTEN TO NO NEGATIVITY ABOUT THIS FILM.....IT'S REALLY A WONDER TO BEHOLD
